05538nam a22007695i 9780231544153DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018050562  a97802315441537 a10.7312/vaug182402doi  a(DE-B1597)526843  a(OCoLC)1096518943  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY10aPN1993.5.A1 7aPER0040302bisacsh1 aVaughan, Hunter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHollywood's Dirtiest Secret :bThe Hidden Environmental Costs of the Movies /cHunter Vaughan. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b26 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm and Culture Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION. The Big Picture -- tCHAPTER ONE. Burning Down the House: Fire, Explosion, and the Eco-ethics of Destruction Spectacle -- tCHAPTER TWO. “Five Hundred Thousand Kilowatts of Stardust”: Water and Resource Use in Movies and the Marketing of Nature -- tCHAPTER THREE. Wind of Change: New Screen Technologies, the Visualization of Invisible Environmental Threats, and the Materiality of the Virtual -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Apocalypse Tomorrow: The Myth of Earth’s End in the Digital Era -- tCHAPTER FIVE. The Fifth Element: Hollywood as Invasive Species and the Human Side of Environmental Media -- tCONCLUSION. An Element of Hope -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tFilmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn an era when many businesses have come under scrutiny for their environmental impact, the film industry has for the most part escaped criticism and regulation. Its practices are more diffuse; its final product, less tangible; and Hollywood has adopted public-relations strategies that portray it as environmentally conscious. In Hollywood’s Dirtiest Secret, Hunter Vaughan offers a new history of the movies from an environmental perspective, arguing that how we make and consume films has serious ecological consequences.Bringing together environmental humanities, science communication, and social ethics, Hollywood’s Dirtiest Secret is a pathbreaking consideration of the film industry’s environmental impact that examines how our cultural prioritization of spectacle has distracted us from its material consequences and natural-resource use. Vaughan examines the environmental effects of filmmaking from Hollywood classics to the digital era, considering how popular screen media shapes and reflects our understanding of the natural world. He recounts the production histories of major blockbusters—Gone with the Wind, Singin’ in the Rain, Twister, and Avatar—situating them in the contexts of the development of the film industry, popular environmentalism, and the proliferation of digital technologies. Emphasizing the materiality of media, Vaughan interweaves details of the hidden environmental consequences of specific filmmaking practices, from water use to server farms, within a larger critical portrait of social perceptions and valuations of the natural world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion picture industryxEnvironmental aspects. 0aMotion picturesxProduction and directionxEnvironmental aspects. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2019z9783110605785oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishz978311061001708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz97831106